  "prompt": "What type of grapes are used to make wine?",
  "response": "Various types of grapes are used to make wine, but they generally fall into two main categories: red grapes and white grapes. Here are some common varieties within these categories:\n\n### Red Grapes\n1. **Cabernet Sauvignon**: Known for its rich flavor and high tannin content, often producing full-bodied wines.\n2. **Merlot**: Softer and fruitier than Cabernet Sauvignon, it is approachable and versatile.\n3. **Pinot Noir**: Known for its lighter body and complex flavors, it thrives in cooler climates.\n4. **Syrah/Shiraz**: Produces bold, spicy wines, with variations depending on the region (e.g., Syrah in France, Shiraz in Australia).\n5. **Zinfandel**: Known for its jammy fruit flavors and often has a peppery spice.\n6. **Malbec**: Originally from France but popular in Argentina, known for its dark fruit flavors and smooth tannins.\n\n### White Grapes\n1. **Chardonnay**: Versatile and popular, can be oaked or unoaked, producing a range of flavors from buttery to crisp and mineral.\n2. **Sauvignon Blanc**: Known for its crisp acidity and citrus flavors, often with herbal notes.\n3. **Riesling**: Ranges from dry to very sweet, with floral and fruity aromas.\n4. **Pinot Grigio/Gris**: Light and fresh, often with pear and citrus notes.\n5. **Gew\u00fcrztraminer**: Highly aromatic wine with floral notes and spicy undertones, often off-dry.\n6. **Semillon**: Often blended with Sauvignon Blanc, known for its rich texture and ability to age.\n\n### Other Grapes\nThere are many other grape varieties used in wine production worldwide, including Tempranillo, Sangiovese, Barbera, Grenache, and many indigenous varieties from different wine regions.\n\nIn addition to these, hybrid grapes and lesser-known varieties are also used in specific regions, contributing to the diversity of wine available globally.",
